<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-shortest-distance" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Shortest distance from a point to a plane</title>

 <p>
We can find the shortest distance <m>D</m> from a point <m>P = (x_0, y_0, z_0)</m> to a plane 
<m>\p</m> with general <m>ax+by + cz = d</m> by using projection. Let <m>Q</m> be the point on 
<m>\p</m> closest to <m>P</m>. Let <m>A = (x, y, z)</m> be any point on the plane. The setup is 
shown in <xref ref="fig-plane_dist"/>. Then

<figure xml:id="fig-plane_dist">
<caption>The shortest distance from <m>P</m> to the plane is <m>\|\overrightarrow{PQ}\|</m></caption>
<!--plane_dist.tikz-->
</figure>

<md>
<mrow>
D \amp  = \|\overrightarrow{PQ}\| = \|\operatorname{proj}_{\vect{n}}({\overrightarrow{AP}})\|                                                                             \\
\amp  = \Bigl\|\frac{\overrightarrow{AP}\cdot \vect{n}}{\vect{n}\cdot \vect{n}}\vect{n}\Bigr\| = \frac{|\overrightarrow{AP}\cdot \vect{n}|}{\|\vect{n}\|^2}\|\vect{n}\| \\
\amp  = \frac{|\overrightarrow{AP}\cdot \vect{n}|}{\|\vect{n}\|.}
</mrow>
</md>
Calculating using components,
<md>
<mrow>
|\overrightarrow{AP}\cdot \vect{n}| \amp  = |[x_0 - x, y_0 - y, z_0 - z] \cdot [a, b, c]| \\
\amp  = |a(x_0 - x) + b(y_0 - y) + c(z_0 - z)|        \\
\amp  = |ax_0 + by_0 + cz_0 - (ax + by + cz)|         \\
\amp  = |ax_0 + by_0 + cz_0 - d|
</mrow>
</md>.
Finally, we substitute this into our formula for <m>D</m>. This gives that the distance from a 
point <m>P = (x_0, y_0, z_0)</m> to the plane <m>\p:\, ax+by + cz= d</m> is
<me>
D = \frac{|ax_0 + by_0 + cz_0 - d|}{\sqrt{a^2 + b^2 + c^2}}
</me>.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-dist-pt-to-plane">
<statement>
<p>
The distance from the point <m>Q = (1, 1, -1)</m> to the plane with general equation <m>x - 2y + 3z = 4</m> 
is
<md>
<mrow>
D \amp  = \frac{|1\cdot 1 - 2\cdot 1 + 3(-1) - 4|}{\sqrt{1^2 + (-2)^2 + 3^2}} \\
\amp  = \frac{|1-2-3-4|}{\sqrt{1+4+9}} = \frac{8}{\sqrt{14}}.\
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

</section>